%I A398163 #13 Jul 23 2026 23:00:21
%S A398163 1,2,5,6,7,10,13,14,15,16,21,22,23,26,29,30,31,32,33,34,37,38,39,40,
%T A398163 41,42,46,47,53,54,55,56,57,58,61,64,65,66,69,70,73,77,78,79,80,81,82,
%U A398163 85,86,87,88,93,94,95,96,101,102,103,104,105,106,109,110,111,112,113,114,118,119
%N A398163 Numbers k such that neither k nor k+1 has an exponent that equals 2 in their prime factorization.
%C A398163 Numbers k such that k and k+1 are both semi-2-free integers (A337050).
%C A398163 The asymptotic density of this sequence is d = Product_{p prime} (1 - (1-1/p)*(2/p^2)) = Product_{p prime} (1 - 2/p^2 + 2/p^3) = 0.544527522337261997298... . The number of terms not exceeding x is d * x + O(x^(2/3+eps)), where eps > 0  (Srichan et al., 2026, p. 3, Corollary 1.2).
%H A398163 Amiram Eldar, <a href="/A398163/b398163.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..10000</a>
%H A398163 Teerapat Srichan, Nithi Rungtanapirom, and Saeree Wananiyakul, <a href="https://doi.org/10.1051/ita/2026022">On the distribution of consecutive M-free integers</a>, RAIRO - Theoretical Informatics and Applications, Vol. 60 (2026), Article 22.
%p A398163 A:= remove(t -> has(ifactors(t)[2][..,2],2), {$1..200}):
%p A398163 A intersect (A -~ 1); # _Robert Israel_, Jul 23 2026
%t A398163 a337050Q[n_] := a337050Q[n] = FreeQ[FactorInteger[n][[;; , 2]], 2];
%t A398163 Select[Range[120], a337050Q[#] && a337050Q[#+1] &]
%o A398163 (PARI) isA337050(k) = #select(x -> x == 2, factor(k)[,2]) == 0;
%o A398163 isok(k) = isA337050(k) && isA337050(k+1);
%Y A398163 Subsequence of A337050.
%Y A398163 Similar sequences: A007674, A340152, A367695, A372690, A391396, A398161, A398162, A398164, A398165, A398166, A398167, A398168, A398169, A398170.
%K A398163 nonn,easy,new
%O A398163 1,2
